  <!-- ── CASE HEADER ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Patient Safety</span>
    <h1>Fundamentals 5 — Lisa Rae</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Falls &amp; Pressure Injury Prevention in an Older Adult</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Lisa Rae, 78 years, White Female</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20 – 30 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20 – 30 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── HOW TO USE ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 1 — YOU ARRIVE AT THE BEDSIDE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      You are the day-shift nurse on a medical-surgical unit. You receive handoff report on a patient admitted overnight and head to perform your initial assessment.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Lisa Rae</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / DOB</th><td>78 years old</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Gender / Race</th><td>Female · White</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Admission Dx</th><td>Mechanical fall; hypotension</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergy</th><td>NKDA</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
            <tr><th>PMH</th><td>Hypertension, Type 2 DM (diet-controlled), osteoporosis, urinary incontinence, prior fall 3 months ago</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Current Medications (on MAR)</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li>0.9% Normal Saline IV at 75 mL/hr</li>
          <li>Hydrochlorothiazide (HCTZ) 25 mg PO daily — <span class="badge-warning">HOLD today per order</span></li>
          <li>Hydromorphone 0.5 mg IV q4h PRN pain (right hip)</li>
          <li>Acetaminophen 650 mg PO q6h scheduled</li>
          <li>Calcium carbonate 600 mg + Vitamin D 400 IU PO BID</li>
          <li>Metformin 500 mg PO daily with evening meal</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>
        Ms. Rae is a 78-year-old woman lying in a hospital bed, appearing pale and slightly uncomfortable. She is awake and alert, oriented to person, place, and time. The bed is in a semi-elevated position. You notice the call light is not within reach. A Foley catheter bag is hanging on the bed frame below the level of the mattress. The path between the bed and the bathroom is partially obstructed by a meal tray table.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>🔒 SWIPE Safety Assessment</h3>
    <p>Before touching the patient, perform your environmental safety check:</p>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Letter</th><th>Check</th><th>What You Find</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Siderails up</td><td>Only 1 rail up — <span class="text-danger">needs correction</span></td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>W</strong></td><td>Wristband on, matches chart</td><td>Present and correct — two identifiers confirmed</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>I</strong></td><td>IV lines — site, patency, rate, label</td><td>Left forearm peripheral IV; site without redness; NS infusing at 75 mL/hr</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>P</strong></td><td>Pull cord / call light within reach</td><td><span class="text-danger">Out of reach — needs correction</span></td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>E</strong></td><td>Equipment — bed position, socks, path clear</td><td>Bed elevated; no non-skid socks on patient; path partially blocked by tray table; <span class="badge-warning">FALL RISK</span> band on wrist</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What safety corrections do you make immediately before beginning your assessment?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Immediate safety corrections (before any other action):</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Raise all appropriate siderails (2–3 rails, per facility policy)</li>
          <li>Lower the bed to its lowest position</li>
          <li>Place call light within easy reach — demonstrate use to Ms. Rae</li>
          <li>Apply non-skid socks</li>
          <li>Post fall-risk sign on door and above bed</li>
          <li>Clear the path between bed and bathroom; reposition tray table against wall</li>
          <li>Ensure Foley catheter tubing is not looped on the floor (trip hazard) and bag is secured below bladder level</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Why these corrections matter:</strong> Ms. Rae is already admitted for a fall. Her hypotension and right hip pain put her at extreme risk for a second fall during hospitalization. Every environmental modification reduces that risk before any formal nursing intervention begins.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ As you complete your safety sweep, Ms. Rae begins sharing what happened at home…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 2 — HISTORY & MEDICATION CAUSE CHAIN
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>History &amp; Medication Cause Chain</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      You sit with Ms. Rae and gather a focused history. She is alert and cooperative, though slightly anxious about being in the hospital.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🗣 History from Ms. Rae</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Lives alone in a single-story home; uses a <strong>cane</strong> for ambulation since a fall 3 months ago</li>
          <li>This morning she got up from bed to use the bathroom and felt <strong>"very dizzy and lightheaded"</strong></li>
          <li>Lost her balance in the hallway and fell, landing on her right side</li>
          <li>She denies hitting her head; denies loss of consciousness</li>
          <li>When asked about her medications, she pauses: <em>"Oh no — I think I took my water pill twice this morning. I forgot I'd already taken it."</em></li>
          <li>Has been on HCTZ for 3 years; this is the first time she has doubled the dose</li>
          <li>Reports her urine has been "very pale and a lot" since the double dose this morning</li>
          <li>Prior fall 3 months ago was also related to dizziness when getting up quickly</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚠️ Medication Alert — HCTZ Double Dose</h3>
        <div class="callout callout-danger">
          <p><strong>Hydrochlorothiazide (HCTZ) 25 mg</strong> is a thiazide diuretic used to treat hypertension. A double dose causes:</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">
            <li>Excessive urinary output → rapid volume depletion</li>
            <li>Decreased intravascular volume → low blood pressure</li>
            <li>Orthostatic hypotension — worst when changing position (lying → sitting → standing)</li>
            <li>Electrolyte losses: hypokalemia (low K⁺), hyponatremia (low Na⁺)</li>
            <li>Risk of falls, syncope, and acute kidney injury in the elderly</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>🔗 The Cause Chain — Connecting the Dots</h3>
    <div class="chain-flow">
      <div class="chain-step chain-step-drug">
        <span class="chain-icon">💊</span>
        <strong>HCTZ 25 mg × 2 (double dose)</strong>
        <small>Thiazide diuretic — accidentally doubled this morning</small>
      </div>
      <div class="chain-arrow">↓</div>
      <div class="chain-step chain-step-problem">
        <span class="chain-icon">💧</span>
        <strong>Excessive Diuresis → Volume Depletion</strong>
        <small>More urine than normal → circulating blood volume drops</small>
      </div>
      <div class="chain-arrow">↓</div>
      <div class="chain-step chain-step-problem">
        <span class="chain-icon">📉</span>
        <strong>Orthostatic Hypotension</strong>
        <small>BP drops sharply when rising from bed → dizziness</small>
      </div>
      <div class="chain-arrow">↓</div>
      <div class="chain-step chain-step-consequence">
        <span class="chain-icon">🚨</span>
        <strong>Mechanical Fall → Injury + Hospitalization</strong>
        <small>Right hip bruising · forearm laceration · skin integrity at risk</small>
      </div>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What is orthostatic hypotension, and why are older adults especially vulnerable?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Orthostatic (postural) hypotension</strong> is defined as a drop in systolic BP ≥ 20 mmHg or diastolic BP ≥ 10 mmHg within 3 minutes of standing from a sitting or lying position.</p>
        <p><strong>Why elderly patients are at increased risk:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Blunted baroreceptor reflex</strong> — aging impairs the body's ability to quickly compensate for positional BP changes</li>
          <li><strong>Reduced arterial elasticity</strong> — vessels are stiffer and cannot dilate/constrict as rapidly</li>
          <li><strong>Polypharmacy</strong> — diuretics, antihypertensives, and sedatives all compound the effect</li>
          <li><strong>Dehydration</strong> — baseline fluid intake is often lower in the elderly; kidneys are less efficient</li>
          <li><strong>Prolonged bed rest</strong> — even short periods reduce cardiovascular conditioning</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Nursing implication:</strong> Always check orthostatic vital signs before assisting Ms. Rae out of bed. Teach "dangle before standing" — sit at edge of bed for 1–2 minutes before rising.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q: What intrinsic and extrinsic risk factors for falls does Ms. Rae have?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div>
            <h4>Intrinsic (Patient-Related) Risk Factors</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Advanced age (78 years)</li>
              <li>History of falls (fall 3 months ago)</li>
              <li>Orthostatic hypotension from medication error</li>
              <li>Urinary incontinence — urgency to reach bathroom quickly</li>
              <li>Osteoporosis — increased injury severity if fall occurs</li>
              <li>Gait and balance changes of aging</li>
              <li>Diuretic use (HCTZ) — increases urgency and nighttime toileting</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4>Extrinsic (Environmental) Risk Factors</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Getting up alone at night without assistance</li>
              <li>Hospital environment — unfamiliar layout</li>
              <li>IV tubing, Foley catheter tubing on floor</li>
              <li>Meal tray table blocking bathroom path</li>
              <li>Call light out of reach</li>
              <li>Bed in elevated position</li>
              <li>Absence of non-skid footwear</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You begin your head-to-toe assessment…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 3 — ASSESSMENT FINDINGS
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Assessment Findings</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      You perform a systematic head-to-toe assessment. Ms. Rae is alert and cooperative but anxious; she rates her right hip pain at 5/10.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🌡️ Vital Signs</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Temperature</th><td>36.8°C (98.2°F) — normal</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Blood Pressure (lying)</th><td>100/66 mmHg <span class="badge-warning">Low — post-bolus</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>BP (sitting, 1 min)</th><td>88/58 mmHg <span class="badge-danger">Orthostatic drop ≥ 20 mmHg</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Heart Rate</th><td>104 bpm <span class="badge-warning">Mild tachycardia</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Respiratory Rate</th><td>18 breaths/min — normal</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SpO₂</th><td>97% on room air — adequate</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Pain</th><td>5/10 — right hip; dull, constant</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout callout-warning" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
          <strong>Orthostatic hypotension confirmed:</strong> Systolic dropped 12 mmHg sitting up. Ms. Rae reports dizziness and lightheadedness when sitting — do NOT assist to standing until BP stabilizes.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🧠 Neurological / Mental Status</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Alert and oriented × 4 (person, place, time, situation)</li>
          <li>GCS 15 — no neurological deficits</li>
          <li>PERRLA — pupils equal, round, reactive to light</li>
          <li>Denies headache, visual changes, neck pain, loss of consciousness</li>
          <li>Anxious about hospitalization; asking about going home</li>
          <li>Slightly embarrassed discussing incontinence — requires sensitive communication</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1rem;">❤️ Cardiovascular</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>S1 S2 regular; no murmurs</li>
          <li>Peripheral pulses 2+ bilaterally</li>
          <li>No peripheral edema</li>
          <li>Capillary refill &lt; 3 seconds</li>
          <li>Skin slightly pale and cool — consistent with volume depletion</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🦴 Musculoskeletal / Mobility</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Right hip: <strong>tenderness and ecchymosis</strong> over greater trochanter; no visible deformity</li>
          <li>X-ray ordered — ruling out fracture (result pending)</li>
          <li>Right forearm: 3 cm laceration — sutured in ED, dressing intact, no bleeding</li>
          <li>Moves all extremities; strength 4/5 bilateral lower extremities</li>
          <li>Uses cane at home — cane is not with her in hospital</li>
          <li>Unable to bear full weight on right leg at this time due to pain</li>
          <li>Requires two-person assist to transfer</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩺 Skin &amp; Integumentary</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Skin is dry, thin, and fragile — consistent with aging</li>
          <li>Mild skin tenting noted — consistent with mild dehydration</li>
          <li>Mucous membranes slightly dry</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Coccyx:</strong> <span class="badge-danger">Stage I Pressure Injury</span> — 3 × 3 cm area of non-blanchable redness; skin intact; warm to touch; Ms. Rae reports "mild soreness" in that area
          </li>
          <li>No other skin breakdown identified</li>
          <li>Bilateral heels: intact; bony prominence noted; at risk</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1rem;">🚽 Genitourinary</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Urinary incontinence (stress + urge) — chronic; reports leakage with urgency</li>
          <li>Foley catheter inserted on admission for accurate output monitoring</li>
          <li>Current urine output: 180 mL/hr for first 2 hours (diuretic effect)</li>
          <li>Urine pale yellow, clear — no signs of infection</li>
          <li>Intake: 0.9% NS at 75 mL/hr IV</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why does Ms. Rae have a Stage I pressure injury on her coccyx?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Contributing factors to the Stage I pressure injury:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Age-related skin changes</strong> — elderly skin is thinner, less elastic, and has reduced subcutaneous padding over bony prominences</li>
          <li><strong>Reduced mobility</strong> — Ms. Rae's limited activity and right hip pain reduce spontaneous repositioning</li>
          <li><strong>Urinary incontinence</strong> — moisture from urine softens and weakens the skin, dramatically increasing breakdown risk (moisture = friction + maceration)</li>
          <li><strong>Dehydration</strong> — reduces skin turgor and tissue perfusion to capillaries under the skin</li>
          <li><strong>Pressure on coccyx</strong> — prolonged sitting or lying supine concentrates pressure on this bony prominence</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Key concept:</strong> Pressure + Moisture + Shear = Pressure Injury. All three are present for Ms. Rae. Early identification at Stage I allows intervention before irreversible tissue damage occurs.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q: What age-related changes increase fall risk in older adults?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>System</th><th>Age-Related Change</th><th>Fall Risk Impact</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Musculoskeletal</td>
              <td>Loss of muscle mass (sarcopenia); decreased bone density (osteoporosis)</td>
              <td>Weaker muscles reduce balance and reaction time; fractures more likely if fall occurs</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Neurological</td>
              <td>Slowed nerve conduction; reduced proprioception; altered vestibular function</td>
              <td>Impaired balance and depth perception; slower protective reflexes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Cardiovascular</td>
              <td>Impaired baroreceptor response; reduced cardiac output reserve</td>
              <td>Orthostatic hypotension; dizziness with position changes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Vision</td>
              <td>Reduced acuity; decreased contrast sensitivity; slower dark adaptation</td>
              <td>Misjudging distances; not seeing floor obstacles or step edges</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Renal</td>
              <td>Decreased GFR; reduced ability to concentrate urine</td>
              <td>Urinary urgency and nocturia → rushing to bathroom = fall risk</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You complete your assessment and prepare to score fall and pressure injury risk…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 4 — RISK ASSESSMENTS
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Risk Assessments</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      Using your assessment data, you complete two standardized risk assessments required by your facility's policy for every patient on admission.
    </p>

    <!-- ── MORSE FALL SCALE ── -->
    <h3>⚠️ Morse Fall Scale</h3>
    <p>The Morse Fall Scale (MFS) is a rapid, standardized method of assessing a patient's likelihood of falling. Score each item and total.</p>

    <table class="data-table" style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Item</th>
          <th>Finding for Ms. Rae</th>
          <th>Score</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>1. History of falling within 3 months</strong></td>
          <td>Yes — fall 3 months ago; today's fall</td>
          <td><strong>25</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>2. Secondary diagnosis</strong> (≥ 2 medical diagnoses)</td>
          <td>Yes — HTN, Type 2 DM, osteoporosis</td>
          <td><strong>15</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>3. Ambulatory aid</strong></td>
          <td>Uses cane at home</td>
          <td><strong>15</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>4. IV therapy / heparin lock</strong></td>
          <td>Yes — peripheral IV in left forearm</td>
          <td><strong>20</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>5. Gait</strong></td>
          <td>Weak/impaired — right hip pain; limited weight-bearing</td>
          <td><strong>10</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>6. Mental status</strong></td>
          <td>Oriented to own ability — alert and oriented × 4</td>
          <td><strong>0</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fef2f2;">
          <td colspan="2"><strong>TOTAL MORSE FALL SCORE</strong></td>
          <td><strong>85</strong> <span class="badge-danger">HIGH RISK (≥ 45)</span></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout callout-danger">
      <strong>MFS Score 85 = HIGH RISK for falls.</strong> Scores ≥ 45 require immediate implementation of a full fall prevention protocol. Document in the chart and activate fall precautions.
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ What fall prevention interventions are required for a HIGH-RISK Morse score?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>Fall-risk identification band on patient's wrist (yellow/orange per policy)</li>
          <li>Fall-risk signage on door and above bed</li>
          <li>Bed in lowest position; wheels locked at all times</li>
          <li>All appropriate siderails raised</li>
          <li>Call light within reach at all times — instruct patient to call before getting up</li>
          <li>Non-skid footwear applied</li>
          <li>Hourly rounding protocol — check pain, positioning, toileting, personal items</li>
          <li>Toilet/commode within easy reach; offer scheduled toileting q2h</li>
          <li>Educate patient and family on fall prevention measures</li>
          <li>Orthostatic vital signs before any assisted ambulation</li>
          <li>Physical therapy consult for strength/balance assessment</li>
          <li>Review and reconcile all medications with fall-risk profile (diuretics, analgesics)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ── BRADEN SCALE ── -->
    <h3 style="margin-top: 1.75rem;">🩹 Braden Scale for Predicting Pressure Sore Risk</h3>
    <p>The Braden Scale assesses six risk factors for pressure injury development. Lower scores indicate higher risk. Total ≤ 18 = at risk.</p>

    <table class="data-table" style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Subscale</th>
          <th>Finding for Ms. Rae</th>
          <th>Score (1–4)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>1. Sensory Perception</strong> — ability to respond meaningfully to pressure-related discomfort</td>
          <td>Slightly limited — reports coccyx soreness only when asked; may not reposition spontaneously</td>
          <td><strong>3</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>2. Moisture</strong> — degree skin is exposed to moisture</td>
          <td>Occasionally moist — urinary incontinence requiring peri care; Foley present but prior episodes</td>
          <td><strong>3</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>3. Activity</strong> — degree of physical activity</td>
          <td>Bedrest — cannot stand independently; requires two-person assist</td>
          <td><strong>2</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>4. Mobility</strong> — ability to change and control body position</td>
          <td>Slightly limited — can make minor adjustments but right hip pain limits repositioning</td>
          <td><strong>3</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>5. Nutrition</strong> — usual food intake pattern</td>
          <td>Probably adequate — reports eating well; diet-controlled DM; dehydrated</td>
          <td><strong>3</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>6. Friction &amp; Shear</strong> — movement requires assistance; may slide in bed</td>
          <td>Potential problem — requires repositioning assistance; limited ability to self-lift off sheets</td>
          <td><strong>2</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fff8e1;">
          <td colspan="2"><strong>TOTAL BRADEN SCORE</strong></td>
          <td><strong>16</strong> <span class="badge-warning">AT RISK (15–18)</span></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <strong>Braden Score 16 = AT RISK for pressure injury.</strong> Ms. Rae also already has a <strong>Stage I pressure injury on her coccyx</strong> — this elevates urgency significantly. Pressure injury prevention protocol must begin immediately.
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ What pressure injury prevention interventions are required for this patient?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Reposition every 2 hours</strong> — document each turn (side-lying, semi-Fowler's, etc.); use a turn clock/schedule</li>
          <li><strong>Offload coccyx</strong> — use foam or gel positioning wedges; avoid HOB &gt; 30° for prolonged periods</li>
          <li><strong>Heel protection</strong> — elevate heels off bed using pillows (calf supported, heels floating); consider heel protectors</li>
          <li><strong>Keep skin clean and dry</strong> — cleanse perineum after each episode of incontinence; apply moisture barrier cream/ointment</li>
          <li><strong>Specialized mattress/surface</strong> — request pressure-redistribution mattress if available per facility protocol</li>
          <li><strong>Nutrition support</strong> — ensure adequate protein and calorie intake; consider dietitian consult</li>
          <li><strong>Hydration</strong> — IV fluids currently running; monitor intake and output; encourage oral fluids when tolerated</li>
          <li><strong>Skin inspection</strong> — assess skin at every turn and each shift; document Stage I finding and monitor for progression</li>
          <li><strong>Minimize shear and friction</strong> — use lift sheets for repositioning; never drag patient across sheets</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Armed with your assessment and risk scores, you develop your clinical reasoning plan…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
