      <div class="sbar-item sbar-b">
        <span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span>
        <p>Ms. Rae has a history of hypertension, Type 2 DM (diet-controlled), osteoporosis, and urinary incontinence. She accidentally took a double dose of HCTZ 25 mg this morning. She was admitted with a BP of 88/54, received a 500 mL NS bolus in the ED, and IV NS 75 mL/hr is running. She has a right hip bruise and right forearm laceration (sutured). On exam I found a Stage I pressure injury on her coccyx. Morse Fall Score is 85 — HIGH RISK. Braden Score is 16 — AT RISK for pressure injury.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="sbar-item sbar-a">
        <span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span>
        <p>Current BP is 100/66 lying, dropping to 88/58 sitting — orthostatic hypotension confirmed. HR 104, afebrile, SpO₂ 97%. Urine output has been 180 mL/hr for 2 hours — likely ongoing diuretic effect. She is alert and oriented but anxious. Pain is 5/10 right hip. She has not voided naturally — Foley is in place. Electrolytes pending.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="sbar-item sbar-r">
        <span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span>
        <p>Requesting: (1) Confirm HCTZ is held today. (2) Review IV fluid rate — continue or increase NS. (3) Order for orthostatic vital signs q4h. (4) Physical therapy consult for fall/gait assessment. (5) Wound care order for Stage I pressure injury. (6) Clarify weight-bearing status for right hip. (7) Electrolyte results — please review when available and order replacements PRN.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Medication Administration -->
